<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06019105 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06019105 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  TELEVISION; VIDEO; TECHNOLOGY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  WHAT looks like a toy, handles like a pen and controls your TV with just threebuttons? Behold the Mitsubishi PRM-1 remote control, a paragon of clarity inan age of incomprehensible electronics.;    Designed by Doug Patton, the PRM-1operates power, volume and channel selection on any Mitsubishi TV up to fourgenerations old.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Home  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  AT LAST, A SIMPLE REMOTE CONTROL  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Design of the WeekAdditional information attached to the end of this article.  </MEMO><TEXT>     The remote will not run your VCR or fine tune and lock in channels. What itdoes is organize the basics in a jaunty format at a reasonable price, about$50. According to the designer, &quot;It represents the minimum amount ofinformation needed to get the job done.&quot;;    Patton recently told a gatheringof designers: &quot;It is time to stop trying to dazzle people and instead try toliberate them by making things simpler.&quot;;    True to his word, he has madethis remote so simple that small children can operate it with ease. So canpeople with arthritic fingers and others who have difficulty manipulatingsmall buttons.;    There's something else: It's fun to use, a not uncommondividend of scrupulous design.; PRM-1 remote control; (star)(star)(star);Mitsubishi, 5757 Plaza Drive, Cypress 90630; (800) 552-7278;(star)(star)(star)(star) for best and (star) for worst. Judith Arangocritiques the design of products each week in the Home section. She'spresident of Arango Design Foundation, which organizes design exhibits formuseums, and owner of Arango, America's oldest design store, in Miami, Fla.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  JUDITH ARANGO, Special to the Mercury News  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910119  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday 